# ğŸŒ±The Asymmetrical Structure of Carrier and Consciousness

On one side, in the process of definition, creation, value assignment, and narration carried out by consciousness, the carrier remains only a passive resistor, filter, and settler; the costs generated by conscious activity are borne unilaterally by the carrier, while consciousness itself possesses unlimited expansiveness.
On the other side, the carrier can, through pain, fatigue, coma, collapse, termination, and even death, naturally resist, filter, and settle the unrestrained actions of consciousness; these are not conscious behaviors, but the inherent Tianran Quanli of the carrier. However, from the perspective of the carrier itself, although these Tianran Quanli exist structurally, they can only manifest passively and cannot be expressed; they can only occur passively and cannot be asserted.
The only entity that can knowâ€”and indeed already knowsâ€”the existence of carrier Quanli is consciousness; the only entity that can acknowledge or deny carrier Quanli is also consciousness. This asymmetry itself is an irremovable structural fact.
In social systems constructed by consciousness, ethics and civilization attempt, to a certain extent, to protect the carrier and partially acknowledge the carrierâ€™s Quanli of use, Quanli of settlement, and Quanli of bandwidthâ€”for example, law, ethics, medicine, social security, and equality institutions all, to some degree, speak for the carrier with the implicit message: â€œThis exercise of conscious Quanli is unbearable for the carrier.â€
Yet within the same structure, consciousness imposes its own dominant boundary-cutting and value vectors upon the carrier, destroying the carrierâ€™s original structure (including physiological balance, psychological stability, and boundary self-maintenance). The price the carrier pays manifests as structural irreversible damage, organ failure, mental collapse, and lifespan reduction â€” which can be termed structural destruction.
Whether it is protection of the carrier or structural destruction, both are cross-boundary impositions by consciousness upon the carrierâ€™s Tianran Quanli system, disregarding the self-sustaining operation of the carrierâ€™s Tianran Quanli system.
Therefore, the issue of consciousness being unbound by settlement constraints, and the issue of irreversible settlement risks arising under asymmetrical structure, are neither ethical problems, nor value judgments, nor moral adjudications â€” they are merely physical-structural facts.
In this sense:
Overtime work is structural destruction;  
Emotional deprivation is structural destruction;  
Attention economy is structural destruction;  
High-density ideological indoctrination is structural destruction;  
Forced belief and sacrifice of the body for conviction is structural destruction;  
Homosexuality, transsexuality, and multi-gender identification are structural destruction;  
Self-destruction in religious conversion and extreme self-modification through fitness are also structural destruction.

The asymmetrical structure of carrier and consciousness determines that structural destruction by consciousness is omnipresent.